# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infospace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infospace/360networks] The company was founded as Pacific Fiber Link, L.L.C. on February 5, 1998, as a subsidiary of Ledcor Industries of Canada, a member of the Ledcor Group of Companies, owned by the Lede family.
[src:infospace/360networks] It commenced business operations on May 31, 1998.
[src:infospace/360networks] As the fiber optic telecommunications industry boomed, one of the greatest impediments to rapid growth for the telecoms was the acquisition of the rights of way within which to lay the fiber optic cables.
[src:infospace/360networks] The Ledes came up with a solution to this problem and negotiated a deal with the Canadian National Railway to install the cable in the railroad's rights of way alongside the tracks.
[src:infospace/360networks] This technology enabled 360networks to rapidly lay out a North American fiber optic network throughout Canada and the United States along and within numerous railroad rights of way.
[src:infospace/360networks] The patent for the Railplow was transferred to a subsidiary of the two companies and 360networks received a royalty-free, exclusive license for the use of the Railplow, giving it a significant advantage over some of its competitors that also utilized rail corridors.
[src:infospace/360networks] Initially, the company focused on building a fiber optic route from Seattle to Sacramento.
[src:infospace/360networks] In 1999, it changed its name to Worldwide Fiber Networks, Inc. and its focus toward a global network.
[src:infospace/360networks] In 2000, the company changed its name to 360networks Inc., and its United States entity to 360networks (USA)inc., to better describe its 360-degree focus on a global network.
[src:infospace/360networks] It hired Greg Maffei, the former chief financial officer of Microsoft, as its new chief executive officer of the company and received private equity investments from Michael Dell, Nathan Myhrvold, Liberty Media, and News Corp.
[src:infospace/360networks] In May 2000, the company acquired 1 million square feet of space to house computer networking equipment in Los Angeles, Atlanta and Dallas for $144 million in cash and stock.
[src:infospace/360networks] In August 2000, the company acquired 11,000 miles of fiber optic infrastructure from Call-Net Enterprises Incorporated for $162.5 million.
[src:infospace/360networks] In November 2000, the company had a market capitalization of $13 billion, despite only $234 million in revenue for the first six months of 2000.
[src:infospace/360networks] In May 2001, the company received a license to own infrastructure in Japan.
[src:infospace/360networks] In early June 2001, the company skipped a debt payment.
[src:infospace/360networks] On June 28, 2001, the company filed bankruptcy in Canada and the United States.
[src:infospace/360networks] In October 2002, WL Ross & Co acquired 12.5% of the company.
[src:infospace/360networks] In November 2002, the company emerged from bankruptcy.
[src:infospace/360networks] The company also acquired Group Telecom.
[src:infospace/360networks] In May 2003, the company acquired the U.S. communications business of Dynegy.
[src:infospace/360networks] In November 2003, the company sold assets to Qwest.
[src:infospace/360networks] In January 2004, the company bought the assets of Touch America out of bankruptcy.
[src:infospace/360networks] In May 2004, the company sold its Canadian assets to Bell Canada for C$275 million.
[src:infospace/360networks] In July 2005, Greg Maffei vacated his position as CEO to work for Oracle Corporation, but remained chairman.
[src:infospace/360networks] In December 2011, the company was acquired by Zayo Group.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com provided network interface controller and switches, routers, wireless access points and controllers, IP voice systems, and intrusion prevention systems.
[src:infospace/3com] The company was based in Santa Clara, California.
[src:infospace/3com] From its 2007 acquisition of 100 percent ownership of H3C Technologies Co., Limited (H3C) —initially a joint venture with China-based Huawei Technologies—3Com achieved a market presence in China, and also sold products in Europe, Asia, and the Americas.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com products were sold under the brands 3Com, H3C, and TippingPoint.
[src:infospace/3com] On April 12, 2010, Hewlett-Packard completed the acquisition of 3Com.
[src:infospace/3com] It was merged into HPE's Aruba Networks business unit following HP's acquisition of Aruba in 2015 and subsequent split into HPE later that same year.
[src:infospace/3com] After reading an article on ALOHAnet, Robert Metcalfe became interested in computer networking.
[src:infospace/3com] ALOHAnet was an over-the-air wide area network system in Hawaii using ultra high frequency radios and made several assumptions that Metcalfe thought would not be correct in practice.
[src:infospace/3com] He developed his own theories of how to manage traffic, and began to consider an "ALOHAnet in a wire" networking system.
[src:infospace/3com] In 1972, he joined Xerox PARC to develop these ideas, and after pairing up with David Boggs, the two had early 3 Mbit/s versions of Ethernet working in 1973.
[src:infospace/3com] They then went on to build up a networking protocol known as PARC Universal Packet (PuP), with the entire system ready for build-out by late 1974.
[src:infospace/3com] At this point, Xerox management did nothing with it, even after being approached by prospective customers.
[src:infospace/3com] Increasingly upset by management's lack of interest, Metcalfe left Xerox in 1975, but he was lured back again the next year.
[src:infospace/3com] Further development followed, resulting in the seminal Xerox Network Systems (XNS) protocol, which was completed by 1978.
[src:infospace/3com] Once again, Metcalfe found that management was unwilling to actually do anything with the product, and he threatened to leave and in 1979 he left the company.
[src:infospace/3com] Metcalfe subsequently co-founded 3Com in 1979.
[src:infospace/3com] The other co-founders were Metcalfe's college friend Howard Charney and two others.
[src:infospace/3com] Bill Krause joined as President in 1981 and became CEO in 1982 and led 3Com until 1992 when he retired.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com began making Ethernet adapter cards for many early 1980s computer systems, including the DEC LSI-11, DEC VAX-11, Sun-2 and the IBM PC.
[src:infospace/3com] In the mid-1980s, 3Com branded their Ethernet technology as EtherSeries, while introducing a range of software and PC-based equipment to provide shared services over a local area network (LAN) using XNS protocols.
[src:infospace/3com] These protocols were branded EtherShare (for file sharing), EtherPrint (for printing), EtherMail (for email), and Ether-3270 (for IBM host emulation).
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com became a public company via an initial public offering (IPO) in 1984.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com's expansion beyond its original base of PC and thin Ethernet products began in 1987 when it merged with Bridge Communications.
[src:infospace/3com] This provided a range of equipment based on Motorola 68000 processors and using XNS protocols compatibly with 3Com's Etherterm PC software.
[src:infospace/3com] By 1995, 3Com's status was such that it was able to enter into an agreement with the city of San Francisco to pay $900,000 per year for the naming rights to Candlestick Park.
[src:infospace/3com] In 1997, 3Com merged with USRobotics (USR), a maker of dial-up modems, and owner of Palm, Inc.
[src:infospace/3com] USRobotics was known for its Sportster line of consumer-oriented modems, as well as its Courier business-class modem line.
[src:infospace/3com] This merger spelled the beginning of the end of 3Com.
[src:infospace/3com] In addition to consumer network electronics, USRobotics was a well-known manufacturer of a dialup access server, the "Total Control Hub", rebadged by 3Com as the "Total Control 1000", based largely on its Courier modem technology.
[src:infospace/3com] This key business product competed against Cisco's AS5200 access server line in the mid-1990s as the explosion of the Internet led to service provider investment in dialup access server equipment.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com continued the development of the Total Control line until it was eventually spun off as a part of Commworks, which was then acquired by UTStarcom.
[src:infospace/3com] In August 1998, Bruce Claflin was named chief operating officer.
[src:infospace/3com] The modem business was rapidly shrinking.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com attempted to enter the DSL business, but was not successful.
[src:infospace/3com] In the lucrative server network interface controller (NIC) business, 3Com dominated market share, with Intel only able to break past 3Com after dramatic price slashing.
[src:infospace/3com] It started developing Gigabit Ethernet cards in-house but later scrapped the plans.
[src:infospace/3com] Later, it formed a joint venture with Broadcom, where Broadcom would develop the main integrated circuit component and the NIC would be 3Com branded.
[src:infospace/3com] In 1999, 3Com acquired NBX, a Boston company with an Ethernet-based phone system for small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:infospace/3com] This product proved popular with 3Com's existing distribution channel and saw rapid growth and adoption.
[src:infospace/3com] As one of the first companies to deliver a complete networked phone system, and increased its distribution channel with larger telephony partners such as Southwestern Bell and Metropark Communications, 3Com helped make VoIP into a safe and practical technology with wide adoption.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com then tried to move into the smart consumer appliances business and in June 2000, 3Com acquired internet radio startup Kerbango for $80 million.
[src:infospace/3com] It developed its Audrey appliance, which made an appearance on *The Oprah Winfrey Show*.
[src:infospace/3com] It scrapped the Audrey and Kerbango products less than a year later.
[src:infospace/3com] In March 2000, in a highly public and criticized move, 3Com exited the high-end core routers and switch market to focus on other areas of the business.
[src:infospace/3com] The CoreBuilder Ethernet and ATM LAN switches, PathBuilder and NetBuilder WAN Routers were all discontinued June 2000.
[src:infospace/3com] CoreBuilder products and the customer base was migrated over to Extreme Networks.
[src:infospace/3com] The PathBuilder and NetBuilder were transitioned to Motorola.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com focused its efforts from 2000 to 2003 on building up the HomeConnect, OfficeConnect, SuperStack, NBX and Total Control product lines.
[src:infospace/3com] Due to this perceived exit from the Enterprise market, 3Com would never gain momentum with large customers or carriers again.
[src:infospace/3com] In July 2000, 3Com spun off Palm as an independent company.
[src:infospace/3com] Following Palm's IPO, 3Com continued to own 80 percent of Palm, but 3Com's market capitalization was smaller than Palm's.
[src:infospace/3com] Robotics was also spun out again as a separate company at this time.
[src:infospace/3com] In January 2001, Claflin became chief executive officer, replacing Éric Benhamou, CEO from 1990 to 2000.
[src:infospace/3com] He was criticized for the costly diversification in the mobile handheld computer market.
[src:infospace/3com] At this point, the company's main line of business, selling add-on network interface controllers ("NICs"), was also shrinking rapidly, mainly because many new computers had NICs built in.
[src:infospace/3com] The company started slashing or selling divisions and going through numerous rounds of layoffs.
[src:infospace/3com] The company went from employing more than 12,000 employees to fewer than 2,000.
[src:infospace/3com] In May 2003, the company moved its Silicon Valley Santa Clara headquarters to Marlborough, Massachusetts.
[src:infospace/3com] It also formed a venture called H3C with Huawei, whereby 3Com would sell and rebrand products under the joint venture.
[src:infospace/3com] In 2003, 3Com sold its CommWorks Corporation subsidiary to UTStarcom, Inc.
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks was based in Rolling Meadows, Illinois, and developed wireline telecommunications and wireless infrastructure technologies.
[src:infospace/3com] In January 2006, Claflin announced he would be leaving the company.
[src:infospace/3com] In January 2006, R Scott Murray became CEO of 3Com and chairman of H3C Technology in China, the joint venture with Huawei Technologies.
[src:infospace/3com] Murray voluntarily resigned from the company in August 2006 over his concerns about the questionable business ethics of Huawei and potential cyber security risks posed by Huawei.
[src:infospace/3com] Edgar Masri returned to 3Com to head as president and CEO following Murray's departure.
[src:infospace/3com] In September 2007, Bain Capital agreed to buy the company for $2.2 billion, with minority equity financing from Huawei Technologies.
[src:infospace/3com] Edgar Masri left the company in April 2008, partially as a result of the failed Bain transaction.
[src:infospace/3com] In April 2008, Robert Mao was named chief executive, and Ron Sege president and chief operating officer.
[src:infospace/3com] In fiscal year 2008 ended May 30, 2008, 3Com had annual revenue of $1.3 billion and more than 6,000 employees in over 40 countries.
[src:infospace/3com] In September 2008, 3Com reported financial results for its fiscal 2009 first quarter, which ended August 29, 2008.
[src:infospace/3com] Revenue in the quarter was $342.7 million compared to revenue of $319.4 million in the corresponding period in fiscal 2008, a 7 percent increase.
[src:infospace/3com] Net income in the quarter was $79.8 million, compared with a net loss of $18.7 million in the first quarter of fiscal year 2008.
[src:infospace/3com] The company reported that it had more than 2,700 engineers, with more than 1,400 United States patents and nearly 180 Chinese-issued patents, as well as more than 1050 pending Chinese applications.
[src:infospace/3com] It also reported pending applications for 35 separate inventions outside of China covering a wide range of networking technologies.
[src:infospace/3com] On November 11, 2009, 3Com and Hewlett-Packard announced that Hewlett-Packard would acquire 3Com for $2.7 billion in cash.
[src:infospace/3com] On April 12, 2010, Hewlett-Packard completed its acquisition.
[src:infospace/3com] When Hewlett-Packard split into Hewlett Packard Enterprise and HP Inc., the 3Com unit continued with HPE and was ultimately integrated into Aruba Networks along with the rest of HP's networking portfolio.
[src:infospace/3com] 3Com came close to merging with computer maker Convergent Technologies, abandoning the pact just two days before a vote was scheduled in March 1986.
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks Corporation was a subsidiary of 3Com Corporation, based in Rolling Meadows, Illinois.
[src:infospace/3com] It was sold to UTStarcom of Alameda, California in 2003.
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks was formerly the Carrier Network Business unit of 3Com, comprising several acquired companies: U.S.
[src:infospace/3com] Robotics (Rolling Meadows, Illinois), Call Technologies (Reston, Virginia), and LANsource (Toronto, Ontario, Canada).
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks was able to use technology from each company to create IP softswitch and IP communications software.
[src:infospace/3com] Robotics provided media gateways (the Total Control 1000 product line, formerly used for dial-modem termination) and softswitch technology.
[src:infospace/3com] Call Technologies provided Unified Messaging software.
[src:infospace/3com] LANsource provided fax-over-IP software that was integrated with the Unified Messaging platform.
[src:infospace/3com] The Carrier Network Business unit of 3Com developed an Inter-working function technology that became the first and dominant 2G CDMA wireless data gateway product.
[src:infospace/3com] In partnership with Unwired Planet (now Openwave) and Qualcomm Quicknet connect allowed for 6 second connect times versus modems connecting the call in approximately 30 seconds.
[src:infospace/3com] This product was deployed in the United States, Japan, and Korea covering the 2G CDMA market sample carriers included Sprint.
[src:infospace/3com] It led to follow on products that became core to CommWorks now UTStarcom offerings including the 2.5 and 3G packet data gateway products known as PDSN and Home Agents.
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks/3Com co-developed an H.323-based softswitch with AT&T in 1998 for use in a "transparent trunking" application for AT&T's residential long-distance customers.
[src:infospace/3com] Long distance telephone calls were redirected from the LEC's ingress CLASS 5 switch to the Total Control 1000 media gateway, where it was converted from TDM to IP and transported across AT&T's WorldNet IP backbone.
[src:infospace/3com] When it reached the destination, it was passed to the egress LEC's CLASS 5 switch as an untariffed data call.
[src:infospace/3com] CommWorks modified the gateway and softswitch software to support SIP for MCI/WorldCom's hosted business offering in 2000.
[src:infospace/3com] Although 3Com sold CommWorks to UTStarcom, it retained intellectual property rights to the softswitch technology.
[src:infospace/3com] After modifying the software to enable enterprise PBX features, 3Com released this technology as VCX, the industry's first pure SIP PBX, in 2003.
[src:infospace/abovenet] The company was formerly named Metromedia Fiber Network and changed its name to AboveNet in 2003 after emerging from bankruptcy.
[src:infospace/abovenet] Before its bankruptcy in 2002, the company was financially backed by John Kluge and Verizon.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In 2012, the company was acquired by Zayo Group for $2.2 billion in cash.
[src:infospace/abovenet] The company was founded in 1993 as AboveNet, by founder Sherman Tuan.
[src:infospace/abovenet] It initially focused on 'one-hop' internet connectivity and providing dark fiber to communications carrier customers in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:infospace/abovenet] Abovenet Communications became a public company via an initial public offering in December 1998 and soared 32% in one day in March 1999 during the dot-com bubble after announcing a stock split.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In June 1999, Metromedia acquired Abovenet Communications, including its subsidiary PAIX, an operator of Internet peering exchanges.
[src:infospace/abovenet] Following the acquisition, the company changed its name to Metromedia Fiber Network in 2000.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In 2000, the company acquired M.I.B.H., a networking consultancy operated by Paul Vixie, for $51 million in cash and stock.
[src:infospace/abovenet] Also in 2000, Verizon invested $970 million in convertible bonds and $715.4 million in common stock of the company.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In 2001, the company acquired SiteSmith, a provider of managed web-hosting services, for $1.36 billion in stock.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In May 2002, the company filed bankruptcy.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In September 2003, the company emerged from bankruptcy and changed its name to Abovenet, with Craig McCaw, Franklin Mutual Advisers, and John Kluge among its largest shareholders.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In October 2006, Digital Realty acquired the east coast data centers of the company for $40 million.
[src:infospace/abovenet] In 2007, the company acquired fiber from AT&T and Verizon that the companies were selling to comply with antitrust law.
[src:infospace/abovenet] On July 2, 2012, Zayo Group, an American communications company, acquired AboveNet for $2.2 billion in cash.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In March 1996, Ken Fox, director of West Coast operations at Safeguard Scientifics, and Buck Buckley, a former vice president of acquisitions for Safeguard Scientifics, formed Internet Capital Group (ICG), a venture capital firm focused on business-to-business e-commerce.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Fox saw the opportunity as "the biggest wealth-creation opportunity the world has ever seen".
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Following the "keiretsu" model used by Safeguard Scientifics, the company was heavily involved in the operations of the companies in which it invested and the start-ups would do business with each other.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] One of ICG's first investments was a website called Water Online.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Under the guidance of ICG, in late 1997, Water Online hired Mark Walsh, head of AOL's B2B division, as CEO.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] The company changed its name to VerticalNet, expanded, and became a public company, albeit with limited revenue.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Unlike traditional venture capitalists, Buckley and Fox envisioned that ICG would hold most of its investments for ten years or longer.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In February 1999, the company converted to a C corporation.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In May 1999, it raised $90 million of funding via a convertible bond issue.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In August 1999, the company became a public company via an initial public offering, offering 14.9 million shares at $12 each; shares doubled in value in their first day of trading.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] IBM bought 3.75 million shares at the IPO price of $12 per share and Dell Computer bought 1 million shares.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Safeguard Scientifics was the largest shareholder.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] At the time of the IPO, ICG held stakes in 35 companies.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] At the end of its first month as a public company, boosted with buy recommendations from Henry Blodget, the stock traded at $58/share.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By December 1999, the stock was trading at over $200 per share, making Buckley and Fox billionaires on paper.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] The company was valued at nearly $60 billion, making it the 3rd largest Internet company by market capitalization behind AOL and Yahoo!.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By then, the company had invested $300 million in 39 start-ups and had a staff of 29 people to manage and advise those companies.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In the fourth quarter of 1999, GE Capital sold its shares in the company.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In December 1999, the company raised over $1 billion in additional capital.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] That month, the company established a European operation, with an office in London.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] With a gain of 2733%, the stock was the best performing initial public offering of 1999.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By February 2000, the stock had declined 41% from its peak.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] That month, the company said it expects to see losses for the "foreseeable future".
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By early 2000, the company had invested $1.4 billion in 61 start-up firms.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By April 2000, during the bursting of the dot-com bubble, its stock was trading at $35/share.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In May 2000, the company invested $35 million to form an online patent exchange with IBM.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By October 2000, the stock was trading at $9/share.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In November 2000, the company announced plans to cut its staff by 35% and take a charge of $25 million to $30 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] It cut back its investments in Q3 2000 to $120 million, from $417 million in the previous quarter.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] By December 2000, the company had investments in 80 companies, all of which were involved in business-to-business Internet services.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In October 2001, after the September 11 attacks, the stock traded for 51 cents per share.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] Two years after its peak in March 2000, the company had a market capitalization of $200 million, down 99.5%.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In February 2013, the company sold its stake in Channel Intelligence to Google for $60 million in proceeds.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In December 2013, the company sold Procurian to Accenture for $375 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In September 2014, when the company changed its name to Actua Corporation, its stock was trading around $20 per share and was worth approximately $700 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In October 2016, the company sold Govdelivery to Vista Equity Partners for $153 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In December 2017, the company sold its interests in VelocityEHS and Bolt Solutions for $328 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In January 2018, the company sold FolioDynamix for net proceeds of $166.3 million.
[src:infospace/actua-corporation] In April 2018, the company underwent liquidation.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan was originally a product division of DSC Communications, a manufacturer of telephone switching equipment.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Original products included a CDMA-based radio platform used for the fixed wireless market.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In 1998, the company separated from DSC Communications and announced Eric Stonestrom as CEO and President.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan originally focused its product line on the small cell and mini-macro equipment market, used by mobile operators to extend wireless services.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Through the acquisition of Mimosa Networks in 2018, the company entered the market for fixed wireless solutions which are used in commercial, enterprise and operator networks for wireless backhaul and access applications.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan's 5G NR development program is focused on mmWave, Sub 6 GHz, Massive MIMO, and Open Virtual RAN architectures.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The company also offers fixed wireless access and backhaul solutions for PTP (point-to-point) and PTMP (point-to-multi-point) applications through its Mimosa Products.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In March, 2019, Airspan announced a partnership with Google in support of CBRS services.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In August 2021, Airspan completed a business combination with New Beginnings Acquisition Corp.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The newly-renamed "Airspan Networks Holdings Inc. then began trading on the NYSE American under the ticker symbol MIMO.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The company was founded in January 1998.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Stonestrom was named president and chief executive officer of the company.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Its first product, AS4020 platform, was based on CDMA radio technology adapted for fixed wireless access points.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In July 2000, as the dot-com bubble was bursting, the company became a public company and raised $82.5 million in an initial public offering.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Its stock price rose 113% in its first day of trading.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In 2004, the company made an agreement with Neda Telecommunications, a subsidiary of Aspen Wind Corporation, to send radios to Kabul, Afghanistan.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In the fourth quarter of 2005, the company released its WiMAX product line.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In September 2006, Oak Investment Partners made a $29 million investment in the company.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In 2010, the company teamed with LightSquared to market LightSquared's 1.4 GHz wireless spectrum in the United States.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The spectrum is targeted primarily at the utility industry for Smart Grid deployments.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In 2009, the company's stock was delisted from the NASDAQ.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In March 2021, the company announced that it would be re-listed on NYSE American through a reverse merger with New Beginnings Acquisition Corporation, a special-purpose acquisition company.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In August 2021, the company completed the reverse merger with New Beginnings Acquisition Corporation.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The parent company was hence renamed "Airspan Networks Holdings Inc." and began trading on the NYSE American under the ticker symbol MIMO.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In May 2023, Glenn Laxdal was announced as the new CEO.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In 2023 Airspan sold Mimosa to Indian communication giant JIO for $60 million through JIO wholly owned subsidiary Radisys Corporation.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] In March 2024, the company announced that it would become private after receiving up to $95 million in new equity financing.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] The company's stock was soon delisted from the NYSE, and the company filed for a voluntary prepackaged Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing in order to implement the deal.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan's industry recognition and awards date back to 2007 when the company won the 'Best of WiMAX World USA Award'.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan & Jio won the SCF 2020 Award for Excellence in Commercial Deployment (Urban).
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Sprint and Airspan won the SCF 2019 Small Cell Award for Excellence in Commercial Deployment.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Sprint & Airspan Netlworks – Sprint LTE Magic Box won the SCF Award 2018 Excellence in Commercial Deployment (Residential).
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan and Sprint were selected as the winners for the “Best Mobile Technology Breakthrough” at GLOMO 2018 Awards.
[src:infospace/airspan-networks] Airspan and Qualcomm won the SCF 2021 Small Cell Award for Excellence in Commercial Deployment for 5G OpenRANGE mmWave outdoor small deployment.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The company was named after *akamai*, which means 'clever', or more colloquially 'cool', in Hawaiian.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Lewin found the term in a Hawaiian–English dictionary after a colleague's suggestion.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Akamai Technologies entered the 1998 MIT $50K competition (equivalent to $100K in 2025) with a business proposition based on their research on consistent hashing and was selected as one of the finalists.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] By August 1998, they had developed a working prototype, and with the help of Jonathan Seelig and Randall Kaplan, they took steps to incorporate the company.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Akamai Technologies was incorporated on August 20, 1998.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Conrades became chief executive officer of Akamai in April 1999.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The company launched its commercial service in April 1999 and was listed on the NASDAQ Stock Market from October 29, 1999.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] On July 1, 2001, Akamai was added to the Russell 3000 Index and Russell 2000 Index.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] On September 11, 2001, co-founder Daniel M.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Lewin died in the September 11 attacks at the age of 31, when he was stabbed by one of the hijackers aboard American Airlines Flight 11, the first plane to crash into the World Trade Center.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] He was seated closest to the hijackers and may have tried to stop them.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Arabic news network Al Jazeera was an Akamai customer from March 28, 2003 to April 2, 2003, when Akamai decided to end the relationship, which the network's English-language managing editor claimed was due to "political pressure".
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In 2005, Paul Sagan was named chief executive officer of Akamai, taking over from Conrades.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Sagan worked to differentiate Akamai from its competitors by expanding its breadth of services.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Under his leadership, it grew to $1.37 billion in revenue.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In July 2007, Akamai was added to the S&P 500 index.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In 2013, co-founder Tom Leighton was elected chief executive officer, replacing Sagan.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In 2014 it was reported that the National Security Agency and Federal Bureau of Investigation used Facebook's Akamai CDN to collect information on Facebook users.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] On February 9, 2021, Akamai announced that it would reorganize into two internal groups – Security Technology and Edge Technology.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] It also re-established the role of chief technology officer and named Robert Blumofe to that role.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Long-time chief security officer (CSO) Andy Ellis announced he would leave in March 2021.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Akamai's headquarters are in Kendall Square.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] It started in Technology Square and later expanded to multiple buildings in Cambridge Center.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] It consolidated its offices in a purpose-built building at 145 Broadway in December 2019.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The company's cloud infrastructure services primarily consist of compute and storage solutions developed based on Linode, a cloud hosting provider acquired by Akamai for $900 million in 2022.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The Akamai Intelligent Platform is a distributed cloud computing platform that operates worldwide, a network of over approximately 365,000 servers in more than 135 countries.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] These servers reside on roughly 1,350 of the world's networks, gathering real-time information about traffic, congestion, and trouble spots.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Each Akamai server is equipped with proprietary software that uses complex algorithms to process requests from nearby users.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The content delivery process begins with a user submitting a request to a browser.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] When a user enters a URL, a DNS request is triggered to Akamai's authoritative DNS, and an IP address is retrieved.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] With the IP address, the browser can then directly contact the Akamai edge server for subsequent requests.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In a content delivery network (CDN) structure, the domain name of the URL is translated by the mapping system into the IP address of an edge server to serve the content to the user.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Akamai delivers web content over its Intelligent Platform by transparently mirroring elements such as HTML, CSS, software downloads, and media objects from customers' servers.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The Akamai server is automatically chosen depending on the type of content and the user's network location.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The servers are located in more than 200 countries and territories.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Receiving content from a server nearer to the user allows for faster downloads and less vulnerability to network congestion.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Akamai claims to provide better scalability by delivering the content over the last mile from servers close to end-users, avoiding the middle-mile bottleneck of the Internet.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] The Download Delivery product line includes HTTP downloads for large downloadable objects, a customizable application for consumers, and analytics tools with metrics that monitor and report on the download process.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] In addition to using its own servers, Akamai delivers certain content from other end-users' computers, in the form of peer-to-peer networking.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] On October 9, 2013, Akamai announced its Open Initiative at the 2013 Akamai Edge Conference.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] OPEN allows customers and partners to develop and customize how they interact with the Akamai Intelligent Platform.
[src:infospace/akamai-technologies] Its key components include system and development operations integration, real-time big data integration, and a single-point user interface.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL was at one point the most recognized brand on the Web in the United States.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL once provided a dial-up Internet service to millions of Americans and pioneered instant messaging and chat rooms with AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 1998, AOL purchased Netscape for US$4.2 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] By 2000, AOL was providing internet service to over 20 million consumers, dominating the market of internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2001, at the height of its popularity, it purchased the media conglomerate Time Warner in the largest merger in US history.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL shrank rapidly thereafter, partly due to the decline of dial-up and rise of broadband.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL was spun off from Time Warner in 2009, with Tim Armstrong appointed the new CEO.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Under his leadership, the company invested in media brands and advertising technologies.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2015, AOL was acquired by Verizon Communications for $4.4 billion, and was merged with Yahoo! the following year after the latter was also acquired by Verizon.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In May 2021, Verizon announced it would sell Verizon Media (and thus AOL) to private equity firm Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, and the sale was completed at the end of August.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In October 2025, Apollo reached a $1.5 billion deal to sell AOL to the Italian conglomerate Bending Spoons.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL began in 1983, as a short-lived venture called **Control Video Corporation** (**CVC**), founded by William von Meister.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Its sole product was an online service called GameLine for the Atari 2600 video game console, after von Meister's idea of buying music on demand was rejected by Warner Communications.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Subscribers bought a modem from the company for $49.95 and paid a one-time $15 setup fee.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] GameLine permitted subscribers to temporarily download games and keep track of high scores, at a cost of $1 per game.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The telephone disconnected and the downloaded game would remain in GameLine's Master Module, playable until the user turned off the console or downloaded another game.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In January 1983, Steve Case was hired as a marketing consultant for Control Video on the recommendation of his brother, investment banker Dan Case.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In May 1983, Jim Kimsey became a manufacturing consultant for Control Video, which was near bankruptcy.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Kimsey was brought in by his West Point friend Frank Caufield, an investor in the company.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In early 1985, von Meister left the company.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On May 24, 1985, **Quantum Computer Services**, an online services company, was founded by Kimsey from the remnants of Control Video, with Kimsey as chief executive officer and Marc Seriff as chief technology officer.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The technical team consisted of Seriff, Tom Ralston, Ray Heinrich, Steve Trus, Ken Huntsman, Janet Hunter, Dave Brown, Craig Dykstra, Doug Coward, and Mike Ficco.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 1987, Case was promoted again to executive vice-president.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Kimsey soon began to groom Case to take over the role of CEO, which he did when Kimsey retired in 1991.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Kimsey changed the company's strategy, and in 1985, launched a dedicated online service for Commodore 64 and 128 computers, originally called Quantum Link ("Q-Link" for short).
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The Quantum Link software was based on software licensed from PlayNet, Inc., which was founded in 1983 by Howard Goldberg and Dave Panzl.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The service was different from other online services as it used the computing power of the Commodore 64 and the Apple II rather than just a "dumb" terminal.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It passed tokens back and forth and provided a fixed-price service tailored for home users.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In May 1988, Quantum and Apple launched AppleLink Personal Edition for Apple II and Macintosh computers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In August 1988, Quantum launched PC Link, a service for IBM-compatible PCs developed in a joint venture with the Tandy Corporation.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] After the company parted ways with Apple in October 1989, Quantum changed the service's name to America Online.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Case promoted and sold AOL as the online service for people unfamiliar with computers, in contrast to CompuServe, which was well established in the technical community.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] From the beginning, AOL included online games in its mix of products; many classic and casual games were included in the original PlayNet software system.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In February 1991, AOL for IBM PC compatibles running MS-DOS was launched using a GeoWorks interface; it was followed a year later by AOL for Windows 3.0.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This coincided with growth in pay-based online services, like Prodigy, CompuServe, and GEnie.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] During the early 1990s, the average subscription lasted for about 25 months and accounted for $350 in total revenue.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Advertisements invited modem owners to "Try America Online FREE", promising free software and trial membership.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL discontinued Q-Link and PC Link in late 1994.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In September 1993, AOL added Usenet access to its features.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This is commonly referred to as the "Eternal September", as Usenet's cycle of new users was previously dominated by smaller numbers of college and university freshmen gaining access in September and taking a few weeks to acclimate.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This also coincided with a new "carpet bombing" marketing campaign by CMO Jan Brandt to distribute as many free trial AOL trial disks as possible through nonconventional distribution partners.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] At one point, 50% of the CDs produced worldwide had an AOL logo.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL quickly surpassed GEnie, and by the mid-1990s, it passed Prodigy (which for several years allowed AOL advertising) and CompuServe.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In November 1994, AOL purchased Booklink for its web browser, to give its users web access.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 1996, AOL replaced Booklink with a browser based on Internet Explorer, reportedly in exchange for inclusion of AOL in Windows.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL purchased search engine WebCrawler in 1995, but sold it to Excite the following year; the deal made Excite the sole search and directory service on AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] After the deal closed in March 1997, AOL launched its own branded search engine, based on Excite, called NetFind.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL charged its users an hourly fee until December 1996, when the company changed to a flat monthly rate of $19.95.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] During this time, AOL connections were flooded with users trying to connect, and many canceled their accounts due to constant busy signals.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] A commercial was made featuring Steve Case telling people AOL was working day and night to fix the problem.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Within three years, AOL's user base grew to 10 million people.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 1995, AOL was headquartered at 8619 Westwood Center Drive in the Tysons Corner CDP in unincorporated Fairfax County, Virginia in the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. near the Town of Vienna.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL was quickly running out of room in October 1996 for its network at the Fairfax County campus.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In mid-1996, AOL moved to 22000 AOL Way in Dulles, unincorporated Loudoun County, Virginia to provide room for future growth.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In a five-year landmark agreement with the most popular operating system, AOL was bundled with Windows software.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On March 31, 1996, the short-lived eWorld was purchased by AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 1997, about half of all US homes with Internet access had it through AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] During this time, AOL's content channels, under Jason Seiken, including News, Sports, and Entertainment, experienced their greatest growth as AOL become the dominant online service internationally with more than 34 million subscribers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On August 7, 1996, AOL experienced a total outage starting at 1:00 AM PST that would last nineteen hours and took over six million people offline.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In February 1998, AOL acquired CompuServe Interactive Services (CIS) via WorldCom (later Verizon), which kept Compuware's networking business.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In November 1998, AOL announced it would acquire Netscape, best known for their web browser, in a major $4.2 billion deal.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Another large acquisition in December 1999 was that of MapQuest, for $1.1 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In January 2000, as new broadband technologies were being rolled out around the New York City metropolitan area and elsewhere across the United States, AOL and Time Warner announced plans to merge, forming AOL Time Warner, Inc.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The new company was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Gerald Levin, who had served as CEO of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the chief financial officer, Robert W.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Pittman (from AOL) and Dick Parsons (from Time Warner) served as co-chief operating officers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2002, Jonathan Miller became CEO of AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The following year, AOL Time Warner dropped the "AOL" from its name.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It was the largest merger in history when completed with the combined value of the companies at $360 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This value fell sharply, to as low as $120 billion, as markets repriced AOL's valuation as a pure internet firm more modestly when combined with the traditional media and cable business.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This status did not last long, and the company's value rose again within three months.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] By the end of that year, the tide had turned against "pure" internet companies, with many collapsing under falling stock prices, and even the strongest companies in the field losing up to 75% of their market value.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The decline continued through 2001, but even with the losses, AOL was among the internet giants that continued to outperform brick and mortar companies.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2004, along with the launch of AOL 9.0 Optimized, AOL also made available the option of personalized greetings which would enable the user to hear his or her name while accessing basic functions and mail alerts, or while logging in or out.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2005, AOL broadcast the Live 8 concert live over the Internet, and thousands of users downloaded clips of the concert over the following months.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In late 2005, AOL released AOL Safety & Security Center, a bundle of McAfee Antivirus, CA anti-spyware, and proprietary firewall and phishing protection software.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as Yahoo!, Microsoft, and Google as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Those plans were abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005, that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On April 3, 2006, AOL announced that it would retire the full name America Online.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The official name of the service became AOL, and the full name of the Time Warner subdivision became AOL LLC.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On June 8, 2006, AOL offered a new program called AOL Active Security Monitor, a diagnostic tool to monitor and rate PC security status, and recommended additional security software from AOL or Download.com.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Two months later, AOL released AOL Active Virus Shield, a free product developed by Kaspersky Lab, that did not require an AOL account, only an internet email address.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The ISP side of AOL UK was bought by Carphone Warehouse in October 2006 to take advantage of its 100,000 LLU customers, making Carphone Warehouse the largest LLU provider in the UK.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In August 2006, AOL announced that it would offer email accounts and software previously available only to its paying customers, provided that users accessed AOL or AOL.com through an access method not owned by AOL (otherwise known as "third party transit", "bring your own access" or "BYOA").
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The move was designed to reduce costs associated with the "walled garden" business model by reducing usage of AOL-owned access points and shifting members with high-speed internet access from client-based usage to the more lucrative advertising provider AOL.com.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The change from paid to free access was also designed to slow the rate at which members canceled their accounts and defected to Microsoft Hotmail, Yahoo! or other free email providers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Also in August, AOL informed its US customers of an increase in the price of its dial-up access to $25.90.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The increase was part of an effort to migrate the service's remaining dial-up users to broadband, as the increased price was the same as that of its monthly DSL access.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] However, AOL subsequently began offering unlimited dial-up access for $9.95 a month.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On November 16, 2006, Randy Falco succeeded Jonathan Miller as CEO.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In December 2006, AOL closed its last remaining call center in the United States, "taking the America out of America Online," according to industry pundits.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Service centers based in India and the Philippines continue to provide customer support and technical assistance to subscribers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On September 17, 2007, AOL announced the relocation of one of its corporate headquarters from Dulles, Virginia to New York City and the combination of its advertising units into a new subsidiary called Platform A.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This action followed several advertising acquisitions, most notably Advertising.com, and highlighted the company's new focus on advertising-driven business models.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL management stressed that "significant operations" would remain in Dulles, which included the company's access services and modem banks.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In October 2007, AOL announced the relocation of its other headquarters from Loudoun County, Virginia to New York City, while continuing to operate its Virginia offices.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] As part of the move to New York and the restructuring of responsibilities at the Dulles headquarters complex after the Reston move, Falco announced on October 15, 2007, plans to lay off 2,000 employees worldwide by the end of 2007, beginning "immediately".
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The result was a layoff of approximately 40% of AOL's employees.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Most compensation packages associated with the October 2007 layoffs included a minimum of 120 days of severance pay, 60 of which were offered in lieu of the 60-day advance notice requirement by provisions of the 1988 federal WARN Act.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] By November 2007, AOL's customer base had been reduced to 10.1 million subscribers, slightly more than the number of subscribers of Comcast and AT&T Yahoo!.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] According to Falco, as of December 2007, the conversion rate of accounts from paid access to free access was more than 80%.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On January 3, 2008, AOL announced the closing of its Reston, Virginia, data center, which was sold to CRG West.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On February 6, Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes announced that Time Warner would divide AOL's internet-access and advertising businesses, with the possibility of later selling the internet-access division.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On March 13, 2008, AOL purchased the social networking site Bebo for $850 million (£417 million).
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On July 25, AOL announced that it was shuttering Xdrive, AOL Pictures and BlueString to save on costs and focus on its core advertising business.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On October 31, AOL Hometown (a web-hosting service for the websites of AOL customers) and the AOL Journal blog hosting service were eliminated.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On March 12, 2009, Tim Armstrong, formerly with Google, was named chairman and CEO of AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On May 28, Time Warner announced that it would position AOL as an independent company after Google's shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On November 23, AOL unveiled a new brand identity with the wordmark "Aol." superimposed onto canvases created by commissioned artists.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The new identity, designed by Wolff Olins, was integrated with all of AOL's services on December 10, the date upon which AOL traded independently for the first time since the Time Warner merger on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On April 6, 2010, AOL announced plans to shutter or sell Bebo.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On June 16, the property was sold to Criterion Capital Partners for an undisclosed amount, believed to be approximately $10 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In December, AIM eliminated access to AOL chat rooms, noting a marked decline in usage in recent months.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Under Armstrong's leadership, AOL followed a new business direction marked by a series of acquisitions.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It announced the acquisition of Patch Media, a network of community-specific news and information sites focused on towns and communities.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On September 28, 2010, at the San Francisco TechCrunch Disrupt Conference, AOL signed an agreement to acquire TechCrunch.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On December 12, 2010, AOL acquired about.me, a personal profile and identity platform, four days after the platform's public launch.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On January 31, 2011, AOL announced the acquisition of European video distribution network goviral.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In March 2011, AOL acquired *HuffPost* for $315 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Shortly after the acquisition was announced, *Huffington Post* co-founder Arianna Huffington replaced AOL content chief David Eun, assuming the role of president and editor-in-chief of the AOL Huffington Post Media Group.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On March 10, AOL announced that it would cut approximately 900 workers following the *HuffPost* acquisition.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On September 14, 2011, AOL formed a strategic ad-selling partnership with two of its largest competitors, Yahoo and Microsoft.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The three companies would begin selling inventory on each other's sites.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The strategy was designed to help the companies compete with Google and advertising networks.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On February 28, 2012, AOL partnered with PBS to launch MAKERS, a digital documentary series focusing on high-achieving women in industries perceived as male-dominated such as war, comedy, space, business, Hollywood and politics.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Subjects for MAKERS episodes have included Oprah Winfrey, Hillary Clinton, Sheryl Sandberg, Martha Stewart, Indra Nooyi, Lena Dunham and Ellen DeGeneres.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On March 15, 2012, AOL announced the acquisition of Hipster, a mobile photo-sharing app, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On April 9, 2012, AOL announced a deal to sell 800 patents to Microsoft for $1.056 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The deal included a perpetual license for AOL to use the patents.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In April, AOL took several steps to expand its ability to generate revenue through online video advertising.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The company announced that it would offer gross rating point (GRP) guarantee for online video, mirroring the television-ratings system and guaranteeing audience delivery for online-video advertising campaigns bought across its properties.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This announcement came just days before the Digital Content NewFront (DCNF) a two-week event held by AOL, Google, Hulu, Microsoft, Vevo and Yahoo to showcase the participating sites' digital video offerings.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The DCNF was conducted in advance of the traditional television upfronts in the hope of diverting more advertising money into the digital space.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On April 24, the company launched the AOL On network, a single website for its video output.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In February 2013, AOL reported its fourth quarter revenue of $599.5 million, its first growth in quarterly revenue in eight years.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In August 2013, Armstrong announced that Patch Media would scale back or sell hundreds of its local news sites.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Not long afterward, layoffs began, with up to 500 out of 1,100 positions initially impacted.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On January 15, 2014, Patch Media was spun off, and majority ownership was held by Hale Global.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] By the end of 2014, AOL controlled 0.74% of the global advertising market, well behind industry leader Google's 31.4%.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On January 23, 2014, AOL acquired Gravity, a software startup that tracked users' online behavior and tailored ads and content based on their interests, for $83 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The deal, which included approximately 40 Gravity employees and the company's personalization technology, was Armstrong's fourth-largest deal since taking command in 2009.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Later that year, AOL acquired Vidible, a company that developed technology to help websites run video content from other publishers, and help video publishers sell their content to these websites.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The deal, which was announced December 1, 2014, was reportedly worth roughly $50 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On July 16, 2014, AOL earned an Emmy nomination for the AOL original series *The Future Starts Here* in the News and Documentary category.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This came days after AOL earned its first Primetime Emmy Award nomination and win for *Park Bench with Steve Buscemi* in the Outstanding Short Form Variety Series.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Created and hosted by Tiffany Shlain, the series focused on humans' relationship with technology and featured episodes such as "The Future of Our Species", "Why We Love Robots" and "A Case for Optimism".
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On May 12, 2015, Verizon announced plans to buy AOL for $50 per share in a deal valued at $4.4 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The transaction was completed on June 23.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Armstrong, who continued to lead the firm following regulatory approval, called the deal the logical next step for AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] "If you look forward five years, you're going to be in a space where there are going to be massive, global-scale networks, and there's no better partner for us to go forward with than Verizon." he said.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] "It's really not about selling the company today.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Analyst David Bank said he thought the deal made sense for Verizon.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The deal will broaden Verizon's advertising sales platforms and increase its video production ability through websites such as *HuffPost*, TechCrunch, and Engadget.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] However, Craig Moffett said it was unlikely the deal would make a big difference to Verizon's bottom line.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL had about two million dial-up subscribers at the time of the buyout.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The announcement caused AOL's stock price to rise 17%, while Verizon's stock price dropped slightly.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Shortly before the Verizon purchase, on April 14, 2015, AOL launched ONE by AOL, a digital marketing programmatic platform that unifies buying channels and audience management platforms to track and optimize campaigns over multiple screens.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Later that year, on September 15, AOL expanded the product with ONE by AOL: Creative, which is geared towards creative and media agencies to similarly connect marketing and ad distribution efforts.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On May 8, 2015, AOL reported its first-quarter revenue of $625.1 million, $483.5 million of which came from advertising and related operations, marking a 7% increase from Q1 2014.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Over that year, the AOL Platforms division saw a 21% increase in revenue, but a drop in adjusted OIBDA due to increased investments in the company's video and programmatic platforms.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On June 29, 2015, AOL announced a deal with Microsoft to take over the majority of its digital advertising business.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Under the pact, as many as 1,200 Microsoft employees involved with the business will be transferred to AOL, and the company will take over the sale of display, video, and mobile ads on various Microsoft platforms in nine countries, including Brazil, Canada, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Additionally, Google Search will be replaced on AOL properties with Bing—which will display advertising sold by Microsoft.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Both advertising deals are subject to affiliate marketing revenue sharing.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On September 3, 2015, AOL agreed to buy Millennial Media for $238 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On October 23, 2015, AOL completed the acquisition.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On October 1, 2015, Go90, a free ad-supported mobile video service aimed at young adult and teen viewers that Verizon owns and AOL oversees and operates, launched its content publicly after months of beta testing.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The initial launch line-up included content from Comedy Central, HuffPost, Nerdist News, Univision News, Vice, ESPN and MTV.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On April 20, 2016, AOL acquired virtual reality studio RYOT to bring immersive 360 degree video and VR content to HuffPost's global audience across desktop, mobile, and apps.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In July 2016, Verizon Communications announced its intent to purchase the core internet business of Yahoo!.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Verizon merged AOL with Yahoo into a new company called "Oath Inc.", which in January 2019 rebranded itself as Verizon Media.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In April 2018, Oath Inc. sold Moviefone to MoviePass Parent Helios and Matheson Analytics.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In November 2020 the *Huffington Post* was sold to BuzzFeed in a stock deal.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On May 3, 2021, Verizon announced it would sell 90 percent of its Verizon Media division to Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, becoming the second independent incarnation of Yahoo Inc.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2025, AOL ended its dial-up internet service.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In October 2025, Bending Spoons acquired AOL in a deal valued at roughly $1.5 billion.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In a statement, Bending Spoons CEO Luca Ferrari cited AOL's 30 million active users as part of what made the property attractive.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The purchase was quietly completed in January 2026, Bending Spoons then laid off more than 100 AOL employees in February 2026.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL's web ecosystem operates primarily as a content aggregator and digital service portal.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The AOL homepage aggregates news, lifestyle, and entertainment content from major syndicated third-party media wires and partner networks.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In addition to mobile-optimized web experiences, AOL produces mobile applications for its remaining properties and standalone software utilities.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL Mail is AOL's proprietary email client.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It provides fully integrated webmail services and direct links to news headlines on AOL content sites.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL Plans offers multiple online safety and assistance subscription bundles: identity theft protection, data security tools, and a general online technical assistance service.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] In 2017, a paid internet suite version called AOL Desktop Gold was released, available for $4.99 per month after a trial period.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It replaced the previous free software tier.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On January 10, 2018, all versions of the original AOL Desktop were shut down so AOL could focus towards AOL Desktop Gold and AOL Shield.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Following the shutdown of AIM, AOL's original legacy chat rooms continued to be accessible through AOL Desktop Gold until the chat system was permanently shut down on December 15, 2020.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] When it owned the Huffington Post, AOL's content ecosystem featured contributors consisting of over 20,000 bloggers, including politicians, celebrities, academics, and policy experts, who contributed on a wide range of topics.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Several major media brands formerly owned by AOL—including Engadget, Autoblog, TechCrunch, and Built by Girls—became part of Verizon Media (now Yahoo) following Verizon's acquisition of AOL in 2015.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Mobile applications and experimental products associated with these eras, such as Alto, Pip, and Vivv, have also been retired.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL previously operated a global portfolio of advertising technologies and services.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] This included data and programmatic solutions handled through its proprietary ad technology stack, ONE by AOL, which was built on acquisitions such as AdapTV (2013), Convertro (2014), Precision Demand (2014), and Vidible (2014).
[src:infospace/aol-p01] ONE by AOL operated under two separate banners: ONE by AOL for Publishers and ONE by AOL for Advertisers.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] On September 10, 2018, parent company Oath consolidated BrightRoll, One by AOL, and Yahoo Gemini into a unified ad-tech platform named Oath Ad Platforms, which was later rebranded as Yahoo!
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL originally built its user base on Dial-up Internet access.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] While the service retained 2.1 million subscribers in 2015, membership plummeted to a few thousand by 2021 as remaining premium users transitioned to software support packages.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL officially discontinued its legacy dial-up service on September 30, 2025.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) was AOL's flagship proprietary instant-messaging tool launched in 1997.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] At its peak, billions of messages were sent daily across AIM and associated AOL chat properties.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Over time, it lost significant market share to competitors like Google Chat, Facebook Messenger, and text messaging.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] It also included a integrated video-chat tool, AV by AIM.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] AOL discontinued the AIM service on December 15, 2017.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Subsequent iterations shifted back to supporting the 9.X version lines.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Version 9.8 replaced existing Internet Explorer engine dependencies with the CEF engine to mimic modern web-browsing frameworks like Google Chrome.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Version 11 introduced a complete software architecture rewrite while preserving the 9.8 legacy layout.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The freeware software stack was fully deprecated in 2017 in favor of the paid subscription iteration, AOL Desktop Gold.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] Separately, the company maintained the **AOL Toolbar**, a web browser toolbar distributed as a Mozilla plug-in offering immediate web hooks into fundamental AOL platforms.
[src:infospace/aol-p01] The toolbar utility was maintained from 2007 until its retirement in 2018.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In its earlier incarnation as a "walled garden" community and service provider, AOL received criticism for its community policies, terms of service, and customer service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL was known for its direct mailing of CD-ROMs and 3.5-inch floppy disks containing its software.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The disks were distributed in large numbers; at one point, half of the CDs manufactured worldwide had AOL logos on them.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The marketing tactic was criticized for its environmental cost, and AOL CDs were recognized as *PC World*'s most annoying tech product.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL used a system of volunteers to moderate its chat rooms, forums and user communities.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The program dated back to AOL's early days, when it charged by the hour for access and one of its highest billing services was chat.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL provided free access to community leaders in exchange for moderating the chat rooms, and this effectively made chat very cheap to operate, and more lucrative than AOL's other services of the era.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] There were 33,000 community leaders in 1996.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] All community leaders received hours of training and underwent a probationary period.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] While most community leaders moderated chat rooms, some ran AOL communities and controlled their layout and design, with as much as 90% of AOL's content being created or overseen by community managers until 1996.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] By 1996, ISPs were beginning to charge flat rates for unlimited access, which they could do at a profit because they only provided internet access.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Even though AOL would lose money with such a pricing scheme, it was forced by market conditions to offer unlimited access in October 1996.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In order to return to profitability, AOL rapidly shifted its focus from content creation to advertising, resulting in less of a need to carefully moderate every forum and chat room to keep users willing to pay by the minute to remain connected.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] After unlimited access, AOL considered scrapping the program entirely, but continued it with a reduced number of community leaders, with scaled-back roles in creating content.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Although community leaders continued to receive free access, after 1996 they were motivated more by the prestige of the position and the access to moderator tools and restricted areas within AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] By 1999, there were over 15,000 volunteers in the program.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In May 1999, two former volunteers filed a class-action lawsuit alleging AOL violated the Fair Labor Standards Act by treating volunteers like employees.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Volunteers had to apply for the position, commit to working for at least three to four hours a week, fill out timecards and sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On July 22, AOL ended its youth corps, which consisted of 350 underage community leaders.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] At this time, the United States Department of Labor began an investigation into the program, but it came to no conclusions about AOL's practices.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL ended its community leader program on June 8, 2005.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The class action lawsuit dragged on for years, even after AOL ended the program and AOL declined as a major internet company.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In 2010, AOL finally agreed to settle the lawsuit for $15 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The community leader program was described as an example of co-production in a 2009 article in *International Journal of Cultural Studies*.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL has faced a number of lawsuits over claims that it has been slow to stop billing customers after their accounts have been canceled, either by the company or the user.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In addition, AOL changed its method of calculating used minutes in response to a class action lawsuit.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Previously, AOL would add 15 seconds to the time a user was connected to the service and round up to the next whole minute (thus, a person who used the service for 12 minutes and 46 seconds would be charged for 14 minutes).
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL claimed this was to account for sign on/sign off time, but because this practice was not made known to its customers, the plaintiffs won (some also pointed out that signing on and off did not always take 15 seconds, especially when connecting via another ISP).
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL disclosed its connection-time calculation methods to all of its customers and credited them with extra free hours.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In addition, the AOL software would notify the user of exactly how long they were connected and how many minutes they were being charged.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL was sued by the Ohio Attorney General in October 2003 for improper billing practices.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL agreed to resolve any consumer complaints filed with the Ohio AG's office.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In December 2006, AOL agreed to provide restitution to Florida consumers to settle the case filed against them by the Florida Attorney General.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Many customers complained that AOL personnel ignored their demands to cancel service and stop billing.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In response to approximately 300 consumer complaints, the New York Attorney General's office began an inquiry of AOL's customer service policies.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The investigation revealed that the company had an elaborate scheme for rewarding employees who purported to retain or "save" subscribers who had called to cancel their Internet service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In many instances, such retention was done against subscribers' wishes, or without their consent.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Under the scheme, customer service personnel received bonuses worth tens of thousands of dollars if they could successfully dissuade or "save" half of the people who called to cancel service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] For several years, AOL had instituted minimum retention or "save" percentages, which consumer representatives were expected to meet.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] These bonuses, and the minimum "save" rates accompanying them, had the effect of employees not honoring cancellations, or otherwise making cancellation unduly difficult for consumers.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On August 24, 2005, America Online agreed to pay $1.25 million to the state of New York and reformed its customer service procedures.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Under the agreement, AOL would no longer require its customer service representatives to meet a minimum quota for customer retention in order to receive a bonus.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] However the agreement only covered people in the state of New York.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On June 13, 2006, Vincent Ferrari documented his account cancellation phone call in a blog post, stating he had switched to broadband years earlier.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In the recorded phone call, the AOL representative refused to cancel the account unless the 30-year-old Ferrari explained why AOL hours were still being recorded on it.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Ferrari insisted that AOL software was not even installed on the computer.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] When Ferrari demanded that the account be canceled regardless, the AOL representative asked to speak with Ferrari's father, for whom the account had been set up.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] When CNBC reporters tried to have an account on AOL cancelled, they were hung up on immediately and it ultimately took more than 45 minutes to cancel the account.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On July 19, 2006, AOL's entire retention manual was released on the Internet.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On August 3, 2006, Time Warner announced that the company would be dissolving AOL's retention centers due to its profits hinging on $1 billion in cost cuts.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The company estimated that it would lose more than six million subscribers over the following year.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL often sent unsolicited mass direct mail of 31⁄2" floppy disks and CD-ROMs containing their software.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] They were the most frequent user of this marketing tactic, and received criticism for the environmental cost of the campaign.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] According to *PC World*, in the 1990s "you couldn't open a magazine (*PC World* included) or your mailbox without an AOL disk falling out of it".
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The mass distribution of these disks was seen as wasteful by the public and led to protest groups.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] One such was No More AOL CDs, a web-based effort by two IT workers to collect one million disks with the intent to return the disks to AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The website was started in August 2001, and an estimated 410,176 CDs were collected by August 2007 when the project was shut down.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In 2000, AOL was served with an $8 billion lawsuit alleging that its AOL 5.0 software caused significant difficulties for users attempting to use third-party Internet service providers.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The lawsuit sought damages of up to $1000 for each user that had downloaded the software cited at the time of the lawsuit.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL later agreed to a settlement of $15 million, without admission of wrongdoing.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The AOL software then was given a feature called AOL Dialer, or AOL Connect on Mac OS X.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] This feature allowed users to connect to the ISP without running the full interface.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] This allowed users to use only the applications they wish to use, especially if they do not favor the AOL Browser.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL 9.0 was once identified by Stopbadware as being *under investigation* for installing additional software without disclosure, and modifying browser preferences, toolbars, and icons.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] However, as of the release of AOL 9.0 VR (Vista Ready) on January 26, 2007, it was no longer considered badware due to changes AOL made in the software.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] When AOL gave clients access to Usenet in 1993, they hid at least one newsgroup in standard list view: *alt.aol-sucks*.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL did list the newsgroup in the alternative description view, but changed the description to "Flames and complaints about America Online".
[src:infospace/aol-p02] With AOL clients swarming Usenet newsgroups, the old, existing user base started to develop a strong distaste for both AOL and its clients, referring to the new state of affairs as Eternal September.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL discontinued access to Usenet on June 25, 2005.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] No official details were provided as to the cause of decommissioning Usenet access, except providing users the suggestion to access Usenet services from a third-party, Google Groups.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL then provided community-based message boards in lieu of Usenet.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL has a detailed set of guidelines and expectations for users on their service, known as the Terms of Service (TOS, also known as Conditions of Service (COS) in the UK).
[src:infospace/aol-p02] It is separated into three different sections: *Member Agreement*, *Community Guidelines* and *Privacy Policy*.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] All three agreements are presented to users at time of registration and digital acceptance is achieved when they access the AOL service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] During the period when volunteer chat room hosts and board monitors were used, chat room hosts were given a brief online training session and test on Terms of Service violations.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] There have been many complaints over rules that govern an AOL user's conduct.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Some users disagree with the TOS, citing the guidelines are too strict to follow coupled with the fact the TOS may change without users being made aware.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] A considerable cause for this was likely due to alleged censorship of user-generated content during the earlier years of growth for AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] This decision drew fire from MoveOn, which characterized the program as an "email tax", and the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), which characterized it as a shakedown of non-profits.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] A website called Dearaol.com was launched, with an online petition and a blog that garnered hundreds of signatures from people and organizations expressing their opposition to AOL's use of Goodmail.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Esther Dyson defended the move in an editorial in *The New York Times*, saying "I hope Goodmail succeeds, and that it has lots of competition.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] I also think it and its competitors will eventually transform into services that more directly serve the interests of mail recipients.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Tim Lee of the Technology Liberation Front posted an article that questioned the Electronic Frontier Foundation's adopting a confrontational posture when dealing with private companies.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] SpamAssassin developer Justin Mason posted some criticism of the EFF's and Moveon's "going overboard" in their opposition to the scheme.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The dearaol.com campaign lost momentum and disappeared, with the last post to the now defunct dearaol.com blog—"AOL starts the shakedown" being made on May 9, 2006.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Comcast, who also used the service, announced on its website that Goodmail had ceased operations and as of February 4, 2011, they no longer used the service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On August 4, 2006, AOL released a compressed text file on one of its websites containing 20 million search keywords for over 650,000 users over a three-month period between March 1 and May 31, 2006, intended for research purposes.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL pulled the file from public access by August 7, but not before its wide distribution on the Internet by others.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Derivative research, titled *A Picture of Search*, was published by authors Pass, Chowdhury and Torgeson for The First International Conference on Scalable Information Systems.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The data were used by websites such as AOLstalker for entertainment purposes, where users of AOLstalker are encouraged to judge AOL clients based on the humorousness of personal details revealed by search behavior.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] In 2003, Jason Smathers, an AOL employee, was convicted of stealing America Online's 92 million screen names and selling them to a known spammer.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to conspiracy charges in 2005.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to violations of the US CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] He was sentenced in August 2005 to 15 months in prison; the sentencing judge also recommended Smathers be forced to pay $84,000 in restitution, triple the $28,000 that he sold the addresses for.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] On February 27, 2012, a class action lawsuit was filed against Support.com, Inc. and partner AOL, Inc.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] The companies then offered to sell software—for which AOL allegedly charged $4.99 a month and Support.com $29—to remedy those problems.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Both AOL, Inc. and Support.com, Inc. settled on May 30, 2013, for $8.5 million.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] This included $25.00 to each valid class member and $100,000 each to Consumer Watchdog and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL continues to market Computer Checkup.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including AOL.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] According to leaks of said program, AOL joined the PRISM program in 2011.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] At one time, most AOL users had an online "profile" hosted by the AOL Hometown service.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] When AOL Hometown was discontinued, users had to create a new profile on Bebo.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] This was an unsuccessful attempt to create a social network that would compete with Facebook.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] When the value of Bebo decreased to a tiny fraction of the $850 million AOL paid for it, users were forced to recreate their profiles yet again, on a new service called AOL Lifestream.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] AOL decided to shut down Lifestream on February 24, 2017, and gave users one month's notice to save photos and videos that had been uploaded to Lifestream.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] Following the shutdown, AOL no longer provides any option for hosting user profiles.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] During the Hometown/Bebo/Lifestream era, another user's profile could be displayed by clicking the "Buddy Info" button in the AOL Desktop software.
[src:infospace/aol-p02] After the shutdown of Lifestream, this was no longer supported, but opened to the AIM home page (www.aim.com), which also became defunct, redirecting to AOL's home page.
[src:infospace/infospace] The company was founded in March 1996 by Naveen Jain after he left Microsoft.
[src:infospace/infospace] The company started with six employees, and Jain was CEO until 2000.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace provided content and services, such as phone directories, maps, games and information on the stock market, to websites and mobile device manufacturers.
[src:infospace/infospace] The company grew at low cost without funding using co-branding strategies.
[src:infospace/infospace] Rather than try to get traffic to an InfoSpace website, sites like Lycos, Excite and Playboy embedded InfoSpace's features and content into their site and added an InfoSpace icon to it.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace then earned money by taking a small percentage of licensing, subscription or advertising fees.
[src:infospace/infospace] On December 15, 1998, InfoSpace went public under the ticker INSP, raising $75 million in the offering.
[src:infospace/infospace] By April 2000, InfoSpace was working with 1,500 websites, 60 content providers and 20 telecommunications companies.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace was praised by Wall Street analysts and at its peak its market cap was $31 billion.
[src:infospace/infospace] It became the largest internet business in the American Northwest.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace may have contributed to the inflated expectations in internet companies during the height of the dot-com bubble.
[src:infospace/infospace] In July 2000, InfoSpace acquired Go2Net.
[src:infospace/infospace] After the merger, Go2Net CEO Russell Horowitz became president of InfoSpace.
[src:infospace/infospace] The same year, InfoSpace used a controversial accounting method to report $46 million in profits when in fact it had lost $282 million.
[src:infospace/infospace] Company executives skirted SEC trading restrictions to sell large blocks of their personal stock.
[src:infospace/infospace] Jain resumed the role of CEO in 2001, but was soon forced out by InfoSpace's board in December 2002.
[src:infospace/infospace] By June 2002, the company's stock price, which reached $1,305 in March 2000, had dropped sharply to $2.67.
[src:infospace/infospace] In December 2002, Jim Voelker assumed Jain's role as chairman, CEO and President of InfoSpace.
[src:infospace/infospace] Voelker shut down or sold many of InfoSpace's 12 businesses to focus on five core segments.
[src:infospace/infospace] In 2003, InfoSpace acquired Moviso from Vivendi Universal Net USA.
[src:infospace/infospace] In early March 2003, InfoSpace sued Jain alleging he violated non-compete agreements in his role at newly founded Intelius.
[src:infospace/infospace] In April 2003, Jain resigned from the InfoSpace board.
[src:infospace/infospace] In 2004, InfoSpace acquired online yellow pages service Switchboard.
[src:infospace/infospace] It also moved into the mobile games space, acquiring Atlas Mobile, IOMO and Elkware.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace reported $249 million in revenue that year, up 89 percent from the previous year.
[src:infospace/infospace] In 2007, InfoSpace sold Atlas Mobile studio to Twistbox, Moviso to mobile content tech firm FunMobility, and IOMO re-emerged as FinBlade.
[src:infospace/infospace] InfoSpace's directory services were acquired by Idearc for $225 million in September 2007, while the remaining portions of InfoSpace Mobile were acquired by Motricity for $135 million in October 2007.
[src:infospace/infospace] In February 2009, Jim Voelker resigned as CEO and president but remained chairman.
[src:infospace/infospace] From February 2009 to November 2010, Will Lansing was president and CEO.
[src:infospace/infospace] Under Lansing's leadership, InfoSpace started an online auction website called haggle.com, but after one year the website was shut down and its remaining assets were sold to BigDeal.com.
[src:infospace/infospace] In January 2012, InfoSpace acquired tax preparation software company TaxAct, and to help differentiate its name from its new purchase, and that of its InfoSpace search unit, it rebranded as Blucora.
[src:infospace/infospace] On April 21, 2014, Discovery Communications announced that they had sold HowStuffWorks to Blucora for $45 million.
[src:infospace/infospace] In July 2016, Blucora sold InfoSpace and HowStuffWorks to data analytics and data management company OpenMail for $45 million in cash.
[src:infospace/infospace] In a shareholder lawsuit filed in 2003, a lower court federal judge ruled that former InfoSpace CEO, Naveen Jain, had purchased shares of InfoSpace in violation of six month short swing insider trading rules, and issued a $247 million judgment against him, the largest award of its kind at that time.
[src:infospace/infospace] Jain appealed the ruling in 2005, and settled the case for $105 million, while denying liability.
[src:infospace/infospace] Jain's attempt to further litigate against his former lawyers for the loss was dismissed.
